    "ancestors": [
        {
            "code": "pt-PT",
            "role": "superstrate",
            "weight": 0.35,
            "notes": "Portuguese superstrate: thinner than other Gulf of Guinea creoles. Angolar descended from escaped enslaved Africans (primarily Kimbundu/Mbundu speakers) who fled into the interior of Sรฃo Tomรฉ in the 16th century; less contact with Portuguese colonizers."
        },
        {
            "code": "pt-ST",
            "role": "adstrate",
            "weight": 0.2,
            "notes": "Sรฃo Tomรฉ Portuguese adstrate via ongoing contact with the dominant variety of the island."
        }
    ],
    "notes": "Angolar (Nga). Portuguese-based Gulf of Guinea creole; spoken in the southern coast of Sรฃo Tomรฉ island by the Angolares, descendants of escaped enslaved Africans. ~5,000 speakers. Unique within the Gulf of Guinea creole cluster: much stronger Bantu substrate, lexical tone system, and thinner Portuguese superstrate. KEY FEATURES: (1) LEXICAL TONE: Angolar is tonal (H/L), unusual among Atlantic creoles and unique in the GGC cluster; tone not conventionally marked in writing. (2) LABIAL-VELAR STOPS: gb=[ษกอกb], kp=[kอกp] โ strong Niger-Congo substrate. (3) PRENASALIZED STOPS: mb/nd/ng. (4) NASAL VOWELS: marked with circumflex (รข/รช/รฎ/รด/รป) in some orthographies. (5) SEVEN-VOWEL SYSTEM: a/e/ษ/i/o/ษ/u. (6) HEAVY BANTU VOCABULARY: more Kimbundu-derived vocabulary than any other PT creole. Sources: Maurer (1995) is the primary linguistic description.",
